<div id="review_2842064074" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2842064074" />
    <a title="M. D.  Hudson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1478575-m-d-hudson"><img alt="M. D.  Hudson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613573775p2/1478575.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2842064074?book_show_action=true">Jun 01, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="M. D.  Hudson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="M. D.  Hudson" href="/user/show/1478575-m-d-hudson">M. D.  Hudson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2842064074" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18194507116298005018">I read Ravelstein when it first came out almost 20 years ago - it was a big deal then, everyone pretty sure it was Saul Bellow&apos;s last novel, and the period-piece &quot;scandal&quot; of Alan Bloom&apos;s AIDS-related death still being news (Ravelstein is pretty much based on Alan Bloom, Bellow&apos;s friend, and public intellectual who hit the surprising big time with his hest-seller The Closing of the American Mind in 1987). According to Wikipedia, Bloom&apos;s friends still won&apos;t confirm he had AIDS, although the ficti</span>
  <span id="freeText18194507116298005018" style="display:none">I read Ravelstein when it first came out almost 20 years ago - it was a big deal then, everyone pretty sure it was Saul Bellow's last novel, and the period-piece "scandal" of Alan Bloom's AIDS-related death still being news (Ravelstein is pretty much based on Alan Bloom, Bellow's friend, and public intellectual who hit the surprising big time with his hest-seller The Closing of the American Mind in 1987). According to Wikipedia, Bloom's friends still won't confirm he had AIDS, although the fictional Ravelstein certainly seems to die from it. Anyway, the novel was sort of a succes de scandale in the day, not just because it was thought to be Bellow's last novel, but also because coming out as gay was still quite an unusual thing for celebrities, even academic celebrities. <br /><br />Back when I first read Ravelstein, I thought it was a bit watery compared to earlier Bellow productions, and I'd have to agree with that assessment today, although I am not sure that this is a complaint. Having recently reread Humboldt's Gift, I found that the last third or so of that book had a forced aspect to it, as if the inertia had played out before the ending came. There was a lot of character-shuffling and little guys in black turtlenecks busily humping around props for the frantic scene changes. Ravelstein is much cleaner (and shorter) while covering much the same ground, and without gangster side plots. Basically, however, as with Humboldt, Ravelstein consists of a doomed, brilliant guy being described by his friend, a less brilliant, but still pretty brilliant narrator stand-in for Bellow (Charlie Citrine in Humboldt; Chic in Ravelstein). As with Humboldt the novel, Ravelstein fizzles out at the end, with money being bequested upon the saddened survivors. <br /><br />Although nobody does bequests and wills with as much aplomb as Charles Dickens did, but I do like it when novelists treat money in a realistic fashion. When they fail to do this, and they fail at this all the time - Disgrace by Coetzee is a perfect example - the story becomes nintentionally "magic" (that is to say, implausible). Bellow always has an eye on the money, and money plays an enormous part in Ravelstein. For years, Abe Ravelstein had lived beyond his means on an academic salary, but after the surprise best-sellerdom of his book, he is now rolling in it. No humble scholar toiling away in a garret, Ravelstein has champagne tastes, now unfettered with his champagne income. The book becomes an exercise in high-end spending - as was, in so many ways, Humboldt's Gift. Rugs, BMWs (a Mercedes in Humboldt's Gift), a tea pot (worth five figures), Hermes scarves, fancy soaps, hotels, food, food, food, booze...are all lavishly described and often price-tagged. Sometimes I felt trapped on a highbrow version Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous with narration by Robin Leach - all that stuff, much of it brilliantly, horribly white (rugs, teapots, etc.), as I pictured it in my mind.<br /><br />Rich people tend to buy lots of stuff. No news here. But Abe Ravelstein is a professor, a public intellectual and a classicist of the first order - his students are ranked, and sometimes rejected, throughout the book based on their Greek. The material world is a fraught place for many intellectuals/philosophers - being bogged down in the material world (including debts, "loans" from friends, both of which Ravelstein accumulated during his earlier, poorer years) is considered a bad thing. Ravelstein, his giant bald dome whirling with Deep Thoughts, knows this, of course and yet the spending goes one unimpeded by anything approaching a scruple. This puzzled me, although from time to time the subject came up. I mean Ravelstein isn't even a collector - an affliction I understand - he was just buying high end new luxury crap (I think $10,000 for home stereo speakers was tossed out at one point). It is hard not to picture this stuff now - a 1984 bespoke camelhair coat of ghastly proportions at the Salvation Army Thrift Shop, with ancient gravy spots and a torn lining, the coffin-sized speakers like the ones guys in my dorm bought, now sitting out by the curb with the trash, fake veneer peeling in the rain, a clapped-out champagne-colored 1986 BMW with a Blaupunkt tape deck no longer working in the dash that still holds an unraveled (unRavelsteined) tape of Vivaldi's string quartets, for sale as-is $800. All those 30-years-ago meals at high-end French hotels surrounded by wait staff with inscrutable duties, the sommelier's keys satisfyingly displayed on his belt. Yuck. Ravelstein did buy art - old stuff, but from what we can tell, with more of an interior decorator's eye than from a connoisseur's or even a mere collector's impulse. He was big into crystal and silverware. <br /><br />Which is to say I just don't get it. Perhaps some of this has to do with the new millennium's supposed disdain for material objects - you know, Millennials don't buy cars anymore - but virtual stuff is still stuff and it still costs money and it still tends to distract in its accumulation. As a confirmed accumulator myself, I am not being a hypocrite here, I hope, when I say that in the case of Ravelstein, I just hoped for...less? <br /><br />Ravelstein's other preoccupation has to do with keeping his hand in the country's business. Because of his brilliance, he collected people - those students who "got" him and who went on to do great things in, mostly, government. In this pre-Internet age, this consists of Ravelstein being on the phone a lot with some State Department guy who tells him about some Kuwait stuff six hours before the press release. Ravelstein loves this stuff - as some professors do - their big brains influencing world events, not just young, impressionable and wealthy minds. This is, I understand, a common fantasy. I had a marketing professor at Ohio State (!) who was an advisor to Ronald Reagan; I remember he'd make a big production about having to jet off to DC the next day to lend a helping hand with The Deficit or whatever. This guy - he was youngish, always wore a suit, had a suspiciously elaborate quasi-comb-over hairdo of a proto-Donald Trump kind - would play for the class - it was a huge class in a huge lecture hall - Don Henley's "Dirty Laundry," which he thought the height of pop culture social commentary (the song was about four years old at the time - c. 1986). It kept him connected with the "kids" and it sure beat lecturing (I was into REM and the Talking Heads then - Don Henley was hopelessly square, man). I am guessing that to his graduate students, this preening nincompoop was a Buckeye Ravelstein. Does this sort of pedagogical situation even exist these days? Even if it does not, I suspect preening academic vanity is still alive and well in those crumbling ivory towers. It used to be an ideal of mine...when I hear the word "mentor" now I reach for my javelin. <br /><br />Which leads me to my current state of bewilderment and looming despair. Back when I first read Ravelstein c. 2002, I was still a believer - a believer in the Defenders of Western Civ - those Ravelstein/Saul Bellow/Alan Bloom figures who defended the Glories of Greece and the Whatever of Rome and the Shining City on the Hill from the depredations of political correctness and deconstructionism, MTV and heartless unfeeling mad scientists. It's not that I don't believe in this sort of thing, sort of. But some of the complaints about these guys (mostly guys) ring truer to me now. If you strip away the privilege, how much Ravelstein is left? For all his Plato and Greek, Ravelstein seems to have been phoning in his old lectures for decades, stuff he'd put together while he adroitly climbed the greased career pole of academia. Bellow wants to present him as this Giant Figure of Culture, a gargantuan bulwark against the rising tide of barbarism. But what happens when culture becomes mere pedigree - I mean, to what extent is foie gras or a Hermes scarf "culture"? Or if your brightest student becomes a higher-up for the State Department for the first Bush administration? Then a think tank of some sort, the Brookings Institute, a few books...where's all this "culture" I keep hearing about? <br /><br />But what do I want? What is culture, after all? Recently I've been accumulating ancient Greek coins from eBay - the kind I get are common and cheap (I typically pay around $10). These coins have horses and gods and goddesses and urns and bows and quivers, etc. I behold them with a kind of reverence - not only because I can't believe I own a teeny-tiny piece of ancient Greek art, but also because they are sometimes so incredibly beautiful to me. My education is so spotty I can only stammer my way around this - I cannot confidently use a term such as - agape? - the way a student of Ravelstein's could. But I am experiencing, in a barbaric way, something about The Greek that I never, not once, encountered in this novel. One of my Goodreads profile photos is of one of these coins (Macedonian - not technically Greek, but, as Alexander the Great would insist, Greek in spirit):<br /><br />Macedonia Kingdom Æ 17 <br />Philip II (c. 359-336 B.C. ) (father of Alexander the Great) <br />Young male head (Apollo), hair bound with taenia, right / Youth on horseback right, kausia below, ΦΙΛΙΠΠΟΥ above. <br />Sear 6696 var.; SNG 607.<br /><br />This sort of thing does not make me a cultural paragon. With no Greek, a slothful, lummoxy Big Ten education (so close, yet so far from the University of Chicago), I am ignorant, yet willing to be dazzled. Ravelstein, both character and novel, failed to dazzle me. As an exercise in 1980s luxury consumerism and geriatric sexual delusions propped up by Plato's theories on love (see below) it has plenty to offer. Again, I get more Western Civ. frisson from my puny eBay coin collection, from this 4th century B.C. tiny bronze youth on horseback, than I did from Ravelstein. <br /><br />***<br /><br />And then there's love. There are two lovers - Ravelstein and Chic (scantily disguised Bloom/Bellow) - both in their 60s or 70s. And there are two beloveds - Nikki, a young Filipino man for Ravelstein, and Rosamund, Chic's umpteenth wife, ex-student (#MeToo!) and about 29 years old. Throughout the book, the love and devotion of Nikki and Rosamund are shown to he the highest examples of pureheartedness. Absolutely no connection between the old guys possessing wealth and cultural clout (fame of sorts) as being part of their appeal; Platonian (not Platonic) ideas of love - monads and whatnot - are brought up throughout the book. The relationship of power/money/youth/beauty are brought up not at all. Bellow seems to truly believe that a young, pert woman will fall in love with his spindly, bald, liver-spotted self in a sort of self-on-self paroxysm of...love. I mean this dynamic is never even questioned by Bellow or his smarty-pants characters - everyone is so wrapped up in Plato - again, I don't mean "platonic" love - so much big thinking, so much wishful thinking, so much delusional thinking that this basic sexual math is ignored. Of course bald and liver-spotted myself, I find this ideal to be very, very appealing...<br /><br />Nikki is not an intellectual, but he is an intelligent, capable, well-organized person, living high on (Ravelstein's) hog as Ravelstein's major domo/dogsbody/valet/nurse (their sexual relationship, we are told, was no longer active, probably a good thing given Ravelstein's health concerns). Beauty as a thing in itself - would Nikki, paunchy and ugly, but still intelligent, capable, etc. still be a part of Ravelstein's household? As for Rosamund, Chic's wife, she was a former student of Ravelstein's, who had admirable Greek - otherwise she is somewhat damned with faint praise in regards to her other academic/intellectual accomplishments (there is an undercurrent of not-quite-taking-women-seriously in the Ravelstein/Chic world - a woman will no doubt be better at detecting this than I am, but even for a Neanderthal like me, I did notice). Luckily, Rosamund also looks good in a bathing suit, so we are told - we are also led to believe that although she is a very pretty young woman, she is not exactly all-the-way beautiful, a shortcoming that is magnanimously forgiven or at least overlooked by Chic (and Ravelstein, who seems to have a queer eye for the good-looking of either sex). And so I had to ask myself, would she be Chic's umpteenth wife had she not...looked good (er, pretty good) in a bathing suit? What if she wasn't? Would they pass muster, attract such love, Gertrude Stein or Simone Weil? How'd they look in a bikini? Would either Nikki or Rosamund had anything to do with either one of these old, ailing poops had they not been (in an intellectual's way) rich and famous? Of course attraction is based on something - after high school when we are all pretty much in the same cohort of age and accomplishment, it is more of a strict and brutal ranking of beauty and athletic prowess (high school is a lot like ancient Greece this way). After high school's strict who's-hot-who's-not dynamic, other adult factors enter into it - status and power, mostly. Which is why we pine for high school, even if most of us won't fess up to it - it was horrible, but it was brutally simple in a way - and nobody falls in love like a fifteen year old, right, Juliet? <br /><br />Love makes the world go round, right? Or at least it frogmarches many of us - especially those of you with kids - through the day. Love. And, uh, and sex and the sexual desirability of youth. I almost forgot about that. Sex. Yes. Don't forget about sex. Sex. Or, in the case of the old and ailing intellectual, desire and desirability - sex is a lot of work. <br /><br />***<br /><br />The last dismal third (or so) of the book is taken up with Chic's trip to the Caribbean where he almost died from a poisonous fish badly prepared at an expensive, highly-rated restaurant run by a grouchy Frenchman (a truly Ravelstein sort of place - get poisoned to death and pay through the nose for it in unpleasant but by no means vulgar surroundings). This incident is pretty much, from what I can tell, an autobiographical blow-by-blow account of something that happened to Saul Bellow late in life. As literature, it is rendered with all the brilliance of a sick old man rambling garrulously and grouchily about his latest batch of health crises. Rosamund, who suggested and arranged the trip in the first place (using, apparently, her husband's funds), saves Chic's life by arranging ambulances and planes and hospitals. Chic is duly grateful and spills a lot of ink praising her tireless energy and resourcefulness, making Rosamund finally, a paragon of a rich old guy's (almost) beautiful young wife. Or, as Bellow will have it, love and devotion in its purest form, blah blah. Bellow's ex-wives are generally portrayed (thinly disguised in his novels - in Ravelstein she is Vela; there's one of them in Humboldt's Gift as well) as keeping an eye on the estate (or, as the years go by, the will). Watching an old guy's bank account being much preferable to watching his derriere in a pair of lime green Eurotrash Speedos, so I'd imagine. <br /><br />Mostly this poisoned fish ending seemed like an opportunity for Bellow to complain about airlines, health care and heartless taxi drivers and mean nurses and expensive French restaurants on a wealthy enclave on a selectively wealthy Dutch Caribbean island. All of it struck me as clueless, self-centered, bitter and sad. Poor Rosamund! I hope Probate turned out okay for her. <br /><br />But this being said, Bellow could write. The book was impossible to put down, a triumph if not of style, than one of skill, over content.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18194507116298005018" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


