    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_976412597" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/976412597" />
    <a title="Timothy F. Stolz Jr" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32384062-timothy-f-stolz-jr"><img alt="Timothy F. Stolz Jr" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1403135256p2/32384062.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/976412597?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Timothy F. Stolz Jr" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Timothy F. Stolz Jr" href="/user/show/32384062-timothy-f-stolz-jr">Timothy F. Stolz Jr</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer976412597" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5526020791979026601">Saul Bellow’s novel, Ravelstein is within the literary genre called roman à clé; meaning a novel with a key, or a secret meaning that elucidates otherwise esoteric components of the novel’s plot, characters, or setting. Yes, Bellow’s prose is beautifully fluid, evocative, at times darkly humorous, and engulfing. Yet, the driving question is, what was the key? <br/><br/>Those of my own generation are likely too young to so easily recognize, but those who remain with a memory, or a knowledge, of higher poli</span>
  <span id="freeText5526020791979026601" style="display:none">Saul Bellow’s novel, Ravelstein is within the literary genre called roman à clé; meaning a novel with a key, or a secret meaning that elucidates otherwise esoteric components of the novel’s plot, characters, or setting. Yes, Bellow’s prose is beautifully fluid, evocative, at times darkly humorous, and engulfing. Yet, the driving question is, what was the key? <br /><br />Those of my own generation are likely too young to so easily recognize, but those who remain with a memory, or a knowledge, of higher politically conservative intellectual times can spot at least one key to this novel. Those who are aware of the time that held Strauss, Weaver, Buckley Voegelin in high esteem and would scornfully look at the overtly anti-intellectual populism of today’s Hannity, Palin, O’Reilly, and Limbaugh, can discover that the main character, Ravelstein, is really the real life individual, 20th century conservative political philosopher (Nussbaum argues we should not call him a “philosopher”), Allan Bloom.<br /><br />Bellow was a friend of Bloom, both of whom worked in University of Chicago’s Committee on Social Thought. In fact they taught courses together, which examined the nature of philosophy and literature to each other. Among the clues for Ravelstein’s identity is his and Bloom’s shared passion for Plato’s Republic, admiration for Nietzsche, and extensive focus and concern over nihilism in Western civilization. However, the most stark clue for Ravelstein’s identity comes from his stammering “thee-ah” in dialogue whenever he began a new thought. Watch Buckley’s episode of Firing Line entitled, “Higher Education has Failed Democracy” to deduce Ravelstein’s stammering is exactly as Bloom’s was. Much like the great philosopher W.V.O Quine, watching Bloom give an interview never was an impressive affair.<br /><br />I would not so overtly reveal the secret meaning of this novel, for I don’t think I found it. No, I think Bellow made Ravelstein so obviously resemble Bloom that this allegorized identity cannot be the key. Chick, the narrator, whom I took to be Bellow himself (gossip about Bellow’s ex-wife included in this novel), is tasked by Ravelstein to write his personal memoir after his death. Ravelstein didn’t want the memoir to include his ideas, he had already written those (an allusion to Bloom’s The Closing of the American Mind). This memoir was to contain all the ugly and vulgar truths of Ravelstein’s personal life; his sexual life, his liaisons, and his family. I find it undeniable that Ravelstein the novel, is the actual memoir that Bellow himself promised Bloom late in life Bloom’s life. Written in code, with esoteric meaning.<br /><br />One must recall Leo Strauss, the 20th century philosopher that attempted, chiefly, to reintroduce to the world the esoteric/exoteric writing dichotomy and its practice throughout the history of philosophy, especially in political philosophy. This being a review and not an essay on the subject, for which a book is needed, all I will say is that Straussians believe philosophers from Plato to Nietzsche wrote secret teachings in their works. Fearing political danger, philosophers have done this for their close friends and associates whom they knew would not persecute them, or report them for their politically dangerous and uncouth ideas. The key of course was that you had to assume, or figure out that one was writing esoterically behind their exoteric verse, and secondly, that one had the knowledge to learn the secret teachings itself. Straussians believe they hold the secret to uncovering the secret teachings and only share that secret with their elite students. Bloom was taught by Strauss (and also Kojève), and certainly, Bellow knew of Bloom’s admiration for the methodology of esoteric writing, let alone the idea of private, or elite, knowledge to be found within texts. What could be a greater tribute to Bloom, or any Straussian, than to write their memoir esoterically?<br /><br />Reading Ravelstein thus becomes a test of the reader’s intelligence (how Bloom would have conceive of intelligence) and their cultured-education. If you were intelligent in Bloom’s eyes and well-cultured, the various references, the untranslated French, German, and Latin phrases, the obscure references to the Classics, metaphysical jargon, and gossip of then famous academic personalities, would seem natural, if not entirely intelligible. If not, you will simply put the book down, get kicked out of Plato’s Academy, and read something else. Just as Bloom and Strauss would prefer higher education to be. I feel I passed the test offered, not excelled, but passed nonetheless. For example, one of many, the character Felix Davarr is actually Leo Strauss, and Professor Radu Grielescu is Marcus Eliade, his rumored Nazism included.<br /><br />There is a richly amusing voyeuristic quality to the prose. One feels witness to the private friendship and conversation between the real Bellow and Bloom through Chick and Ravelstein. You are also witness to the great conversation of two brilliant men; sometimes exchanging private knowledge, sometimes esoteric knowledge behind the exoteric banter. No different than the inside jokes of years of friendship and the private knowledge of years of intellectual dominion.<br /><br />This book was not written for you. It was not written for me.<br /><br />It was written for the memory of two great friends and their intellectual heritage, their private friendship. We are just witnesses. No matter how much I learn, and culture myself in Bloom’s classical fashion and expectations, I will never ascend the love Bellow and Bloom reciprocated.<br /><br />Some things in Ravelstein, I suspect, will forever remain in the esoteric universe of Bloom’s and Bellow’s friendship.<br /><br />Forever private.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5526020791979026601" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


