<div id="review_53506954" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/53506954" />
    <a title="M." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/563476-m"><img alt="M." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1527699535p2/563476.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/53506954?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="M." class="user" itemprop="url" name="M." href="/user/show/563476-m">M.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer53506954" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14860177078733663271">Others are thrown by what they label (lazily, I think) the &quot;stream of consciousness&quot; style of writing. What&apos;s actually taking place is a forward moving narrative coupled with the reflections it inspires a la &quot;Henderson, the Rain King&quot;, etc. My biggest criticism is that the great charm of the first section disappeared. To be fair, outside circumstances have put my mind in a million places at the time of reading this, so maybe I&apos;m not in the best place to judge. Also, this may be the sort of book </span>
  <span id="freeText14860177078733663271" style="display:none">Others are thrown by what they label (lazily, I think) the "stream of consciousness" style of writing. What's actually taking place is a forward moving narrative coupled with the reflections it inspires a la "Henderson, the Rain King", etc. My biggest criticism is that the great charm of the first section disappeared. To be fair, outside circumstances have put my mind in a million places at the time of reading this, so maybe I'm not in the best place to judge. Also, this may be the sort of book you need to be much older to appreciate. A 23 year old probably isn't the best critic of a book that deals, largely intellectually, with death and dying.<br /><br />If I sound like I'm couching my criticism, it's just that I really wanted to like this book. Martin Amis gushed about it on Charlie Rose, and I enjoyed "Henderson, the Rain King" so much that I really had my hopes up.<br /><br />Also, I thought the way the narrator acknowledged his religiosity wasn't an intellectually respected position, but one he held nonetheless was endearing. That was stepped on a little however by this censorial passage near the end of the book:<br /><br />"If Ravelstein the atheist-materialist had implicitly told me that he would see me sooner or later, he meant that he did not accept the grave to be the end. Nobody can and nobody does accept this. We just talk tough...The flesh would shrink and go, the blood would dry, but no one believes in his mind of minds or heart of hearts that the pictures do stop."<br /><br />Really? Argh.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14860177078733663271" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


